    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n                <jats:p>\n                  The emergence of SARS-CoV-2 in late 2019, and the subsequent COVID-19 pandemic, has led to substantial mortality, together with mass global disruption. There is an urgent need for novel antiviral drugs for therapeutic or prophylactic application. Cathepsin L is a key host cysteine protease utilized by coronaviruses for cell entry and is recognized as a promising drug target. The marine natural product, gallinamide A and several synthetic analogues, were identified as potent inhibitors of cathepsin L activity with IC\n                  <jats:sub>50</jats:sub>\n                  values in the picomolar range. Lead molecules possessed selectivity over cathepsin B and other related human cathepsin proteases and did not exhibit inhibitory activity against viral proteases Mpro and PLpro. We demonstrate that gallinamide A and two lead analogues potently inhibit SARS-CoV-2 infection\n                  <jats:italic>in vitro</jats:italic>\n                  , with EC\n                  <jats:sub>50</jats:sub>\n                  values in the nanomolar range, thus further highlighting the potential of cathepsin L as a COVID-19 antiviral drug target.\n                </jats:p>",
    "DOI": "10.1101/2020.12.23.424111",
